[h2 id=RandomItemAssignment 
	" Random item assignment
	$LF
]h2
[div class=p 
	"The location of all items is randomized,
	$LF
	"except for the Watering Can, which is
	$LF
	[a href=https://archive.org/details/msdos_Mixed-Up_Mother_Goose_1987_feelies/page/n14/mode/1up rel=noopener external nofollow 
		"always in room 45
	]a
	".
	$LF
	"The random item assignment code is in
	$LF
	[a href=http://agiwiki.sierrahelp.com/index.php?title=Logic_Resource_(AGI) rel=noopener external nofollow 
		"logic resource
	]a
	" 0.
	$LF
	"It happens once, when a new game is started.
	$LF
	"The 
	(__wikiLink|displaytext=random number generator|href=/Forum/Posts/515748)
	$LF
	"is seeded from the current time
	$LF
	"(an 
	[a href=https://www.delorie.com/djgpp/doc/rbinter/id/80/22.html rel=noopener external nofollow 
		"18.2 Hz 16-bit counter
	]a
	").
	$LF
]div
[div class=p 
	"See 
	(__wikiLink|href=/Forum/Posts/515748|implicitdisplaytext=Forum/Posts/515748)
	$LF
	"for details of the random number generator
	$LF
	"and the item assignment algorithm.
	$LF
	[a href=https://www.bamsoftware.com/computers/tasvideos/mumg-assign.csv rel=noopener external nofollow 
		"mumg-assign.csv
	]a
	$LF
	"shows the item assignment for every random seed.
	$LF
]div
[h2 id=GameMechanics 
	" Game mechanics
	$LF
]h2
[h3 id=Movement 
	" Movement
	$LF
]h3
[div class=p 
	"The player character can move 1 pixel per
	$LF
	[a href=http://agiwiki.sierrahelp.com/index.php?title=AGI_Specifications:_Chapter_3_-_AGI_Internals#Interpreter_work_cycle rel=noopener external nofollow 
		"game cycle
	]a
	$LF
	"(horizontally or vertically or both).
	$LF
	"It may look like the player moves 2 pixels per cycle horizontally,
	$LF
	"but that is because the game's graphics are stretched 2× horizontally—internally,
	$LF
	"the x-coordinate only changes by 1 unit.
	$LF
	"If you need to move both horizontally and vertically,
	$LF
	"the time needed is proportional to the 
	[em 
		"maximum
	]em
	$LF
	"of the horizontal and vertical distances (
	[a href=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chebyshev_distance rel=noopener external nofollow 
		"Chebyshev distance
	]a
	").
	$LF
	"The walkable area of rooms is usually 160 pixels wide and 80 pixels tall, but there are many exceptions.
	$LF
]div
[div class=p 
	"Collection and delivery of items
	$LF
	"is usually triggered by being within
	$LF
	"a certain radius of a certain point.
	$LF
	"For example, the graphic below shows the delivery radius of Jack in room 33.
	$LF
	"The delivery area is diamond-shaped
	$LF
	"because that is the shape of a circle
	$LF
	"in the way the game measures 
	[a href=http://agiwiki.sierrahelp.com/index.php?title=Distance rel=noopener external nofollow 
		"distance
	]a
	".
	$LF
]div
[div class=p 
	[a href=https://www.bamsoftware.com/computers/tasvideos/mumg-E5-deliver.svg rel=noopener external nofollow 
		[img alt=Picture of room 33 with the delivery radius around Jack highlighted. class=embed mw-100 src=https://www.bamsoftware.com/computers/tasvideos/mumg-E5-deliver.png 
		]img
	]a
	$LF
]div
[div class=p 
	"Most interaction areas are a radius like this, but not all.
	$LF
	"For example, Old King Cole in room 37
	$LF
	"has a rectangular delivery area.
	$LF
	"In general, you
	$LF
	"have to check the logic code in every case.
	$LF
]div
[div class=p 
	"The goal is not necessarily to enter the delivery area as quickly as possible.
	$LF
	"Starting a deliver cutscene slows the game down to Normal speed,
	$LF
	"and then the player character usually moves to a fixed waypoint under
	$LF
	[a href=http://agiwiki.sierrahelp.com/index.php?title=Program.control rel=noopener external nofollow 
		"program control
	]a
	".
	$LF
	"It is usually worth spending extra time moving
	$LF
	"to a favorable point at the edge of the delivery area,
	$LF
	"to minimize the distance to the first waypoint
	$LF
	"for the player character to move there slowly and automatically.
	$LF
]div
[h4 id=MovementCarryover 
	" Movement carryover
	$LF
]h4
[div class=p 
	"Many effects in AGI are driven by serial state updates
	$LF
	"to flags or variables.
	$LF
	"It may happen that a delivery cutscene, for example,
	$LF
	"is irrevocably triggered in one game cycle,
	$LF
	"but does not actually begin until the next cycle.
	$LF
	"During this "halfway" cycle,
	$LF
	"it may be possible to continue moving the player character
	$LF
	"even though the cutscene has technically already been triggered.
	$LF
	"The main takeaway is that you should take advantage of this kind of movement,
	$LF
	"when possible,
	$LF
	"to move closer to the first forced waypoint.
	$LF
]div
[div class=p 
	"An important special case of the movement carryover effect
	$LF
	"is when walking between rooms.
	$LF
	"Do not hold down the movement key only long enough to trigger
	$LF
	"the room transition—hold it for at least one cycle longer.
	$LF
	"The extra cycle of keyboard input will give you one free pixel
	$LF
	"of movement in the new room, before you regain control of the player character.
	$LF
]div
[h3 id=ItemSwap 
	" Item swap
	$LF
]h3
[div class=p 
	"You can only carry one inventory item at a time.
	$LF
	"If you collect an item while already holding one,
	$LF
	"You will drop the item you are holding and pick up the other.
	$LF
	"If you are in an interior room and currently have a walking item
	$LF
	"in your inventory,
	$LF
	"the walking item will not remain in the room after being swapped,
	$LF
	"but will warp to another room.
	$LF
]div
[h3 id=ItemWarp 
	" Item warp
	$LF
]h3
[div class=p 
	"The destinations of item warps are controlled by a stack.
	$LF
	"At the beginning of the game,
	$LF
	"the 2 overworld rooms left unassigned
	$LF
	"by the item assignment algorithm
	$LF
	"are at the top of the stack.
	$LF
	"Below them are rooms 4, 25, 18, 5, and 33.
	$LF
	"Whenever you are in an overworld room, have an empty inventory,
	$LF
	"and pick up an item,
	$LF
	"the current room is pushed to the top of the warps stack.
	$LF
	"Whenever an item is warped,
	$LF
	"it pops the location off the warps stack.
	$LF
]div
[h2 id=KnownShortcuts 
	" Known shortcuts
	$LF
]h2
[div class=p 
	"There are many places where a room's logic code
	$LF
	"defines special connectivity that can save time.
	$LF
]div
[div class=p 
	[a href=https://www.bamsoftware.com/computers/tasvideos/mumg-D5-connectivity.svg rel=noopener external nofollow 
		[img alt=Picture of room 32 with zones that transfer to other rooms highlighted. class=embed mw-100 src=https://www.bamsoftware.com/computers/tasvideos/mumg-D5-connectivity.png 
		]img
	]a
	$LF
]div
[div class=p 
	"For example,
	$LF
	"prefer walking behind Mother Goose's house, not in front of it,
	$LF
	"whenever crossing from room 32 to room 31 or vice versa.
	$LF
	"The room transition triggers are closer to the center of the screen,
	$LF
	"and you are placed a farther into the new room, not at the edge.
	$LF
]div
[h3 id=OutOfBoundsInShoeHouseRoom44 
	" Out of bounds in shoe house (room 44)
	$LF
]h3
[div class=p 
	[img alt=Animated gameplay capture showing the player walking out of bounds in room 44 to collect the Candlestick. class=embed mw-100 src=https://www.bamsoftware.com/computers/tasvideos/mumg-G3I-oob.gif 
	]img
	$LF
]div
[div class=p 
	[a href=https://www.bamsoftware.com/computers/tasvideos/mumg-G3I-priority-exploded.svg rel=noopener external nofollow 
		[img alt=The priority of room 44, with a 4× zoom near the door showing that a black line does not reach the bottom row of pixels. class=embed mw-100 src=https://www.bamsoftware.com/computers/tasvideos/mumg-G3I-priority-exploded.png 
		]img
	]a
	$LF
]div
[div class=p 
	"There is a gap in the barrier that defines the walkable area in room 44.
	$LF
	"You can get out of bounds,
	$LF
	"but still close enough to the item to collect it.
	$LF
	"It saves time because you can exit the room
	$LF
	"just by walking south,
	$LF
	"rather than having to walk all the way back to the door.
	$LF
]div
[h3 id=JumpTheWallFromClockHouseRoom24 
	" Jump the wall from clock house (room 24)
	$LF
]h3
[div class=p 
	[img alt=Animated gameplay capture that shows the player walking north from room 24 to arrive in the side yard, returning to room 24, then again walking north but this time close to the wall, to arrive on the wrong side of the wall. class=embed mw-100 src=https://www.bamsoftware.com/computers/tasvideos/mumg-C4-C3N-skip.gif 
	]img
	$LF
]div
[div class=p 
	[a href=https://www.bamsoftware.com/computers/tasvideos/mumg-C4-connectivity.svg rel=noopener external nofollow 
		[img alt=Picture of room 24 with zones that transfer to other rooms highlighted. class=embed mw-100 src=https://www.bamsoftware.com/computers/tasvideos/mumg-C4-connectivity.png 
		]img
	]a
	$LF
]div
[div class=p 
	"There is 1 pixel behind the clock house where you can walk north
	$LF
	"and end up outside the wall, rather than inside.
	$LF
]div
[h3 id=JumpTheWallToPumpkinHouseRoom19 
	" Jump the wall to pumpkin house (room 19)
	$LF
]h3
[div class=p 
	[img alt=Animated gameplay capture of the player walking outside the wall in room 19, going north, and arriving inside the wall in room 12. class=embed mw-100 src=https://www.bamsoftware.com/computers/tasvideos/mumg-E3-E2-skip.gif 
	]img
	$LF
]div
[div class=p 
	[a href=https://www.bamsoftware.com/computers/tasvideos/mumg-E3-connectivity.svg rel=noopener external nofollow 
		[img alt=Picture of room 19 with zones that transfer to other rooms highlighted. class=embed mw-100 src=https://www.bamsoftware.com/computers/tasvideos/mumg-E3-connectivity.png 
		]img
	]a
	$LF
]div
[div class=p 
	"There is a small area outside the wall
	$LF
	"where you can walk north and end up inside the yard
	$LF
	"of the pumpkin house in room 12,
	$LF
	"rather than outside.
	$LF
]div
